data.name: InfoTextbox.Text
data.value:
Destiny 2 Auto-Fisher removes the monotony of fishing through automating the process with the help of some prediction engines.
A detailed guide on how to use this program is available to the right, as well as a link to a discord server should you need any in-person assistance.
Getting Started: After configuring your ‘Interaction Key’, found on the right, to match your in-game fishing keybind, you’ll want to open Destiny 2 and head to a fishing pond.
Once you get your ‘Go Fishing (Bait Held: XXX)’ pop-up, tab over to D2 Auto-Fisher, press ‘Calibrate’, and tab back over to Destiny. The program will give you three seconds to do this before taking a screenshot and analyzing its contents in order to do some starting configuration. The screenshot, and its analyzed output, will be available for you to view in the same folder as this executable: they will be labeled ‘Calibration_Input.jpg’ and ‘Calibration_Output.jpg’ respectively.
Once calibration is done, you just press ‘Run’ and tab over to Destiny! The program will automatically send fishing inputs when appropriate, so all you need to do is stand near a fishing pond!
Once you’re done fishing, you can press ‘Stop’ or you can simply exit the program.

data.name: RunButton.ToolTip
data.value: Begins auto-fisher. Will not work without proper calibration data as set by the button 'Calibrate'. Auto-fisher WILL require about 500 mb of spare memory due to the nature of the prediction engine utilized.

data.name: CalibrateButton.ToolTip
data.value: Runs a calibration routine that finds the fishing interaction pop-up on your screen. Calibration is visualed through the files 'Calibration_Input.jpg' and 'Calibration_Output.jpg', both saved in the same directory as the executable. Calibration should be ran on first time set-up, and whenever your Destiny window moves from its previous normal position.

data.name: RPSInput.ToolTip
data.value: It's NOT recommended that you change this value unless you know what you are doing. Changes how many times auto-fisher runs per second. A higher value will not necessarily produce better fishing results due to the how fishing works in Destiny. A higher value will also slightly demand more performance due to the nature of how auto-fisher works. Recommended Values: No Prediction Engine: 10 - 20 runs per second. Prediction Engine: 2 - 5 runs per second.

data.name: PredictionEngineCheckbox.ToolTip
data.value: Toggle to use a prediction engine for detecting available fishing interaction. This MAY provide an increase in reliability at a HUGE resource cost due to the nature of the deep learning model utilized. It would be wise to reduce your runs per second should you use the prediction engine option.
